.","meanings":["French Canadian: variant of   Madore  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Madore","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Armand, Eusebe, Fernand, Lucien, Normand, Adhemar, Adrien, Donat, Elzear, Francois, Gaetan, Gilles.","French Canadian: from a French shortened form of the Spanish personal name <i>Amador</i>, from Latin <i>Amator</i> (from <i>amator</i> ‘lover’), a Christian saint's name. Compare   Mador  .","In some cases possibly also Breton (<b>Madoré</b>): nickname meaning literally ‘good help’, from Old Breton <i>mat</i> ‘good’ and <i>uuoret</i> ‘help’."]}]},{"name":"Vychan","type":"LAST","meanings":["Welsh: A Welsh name of great antiquity, from vyckan, little, small; i.e. small in stature. Compare the surname Bychan and the Armoric Le Bihan."],"variants":[]},{"name":"or","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Traditional name from <i>mór</i> ‘large, great’. This was the commonest of all girls’ names in late medieval Ireland, and has continued in use in both Ireland and Scotland to the present day."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Arthen","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German: from a short form of the personal name <i>Wartold</i>, from Old High German <i>wart</i> ‘guardian’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"verch","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Otto, Orlo.","German: variant of   Ferch  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Ferch","meanings":["German: variant of   Ferg  . Compare   Verch  .","Probably also an Americanized form of German <b>Förtsch</b> (see   Foertsch  ).","Probably also an Americanized form of German <b>Förch</b> (see   Foerch  )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Arddyn or Arthen verch Madog Vychan was born about 1135, in Denbighshire, Wales, United Kingdom, her father, Madog Vychan ap Mado